sec.p:
It must be noted, however, that the misinterpretation of the General's behavior in the above scenario is, as Kitwood and Bredin asserted, quite innocent for the following reasons:


the staff member does not understand or is not aware of the sound reasons for the anger being expressed by the General;

the staff member is interpreting the behavior in question on the basis of the original pre-positioning of the General as an instantiation of dementia, so that any behavior that seems to deviate from the ‘norm’ or what the staff member desires in his or her efforts to ‘manage the resident/patient’ is henceforth viewed as being symptomatic of dementia rather than symptomatic of dysfunctional social treatment.
